Bay Wheels Bike Service - Usage Pattern Analysis¶

by Laszlo¶

Investigation Overview¶

Lyft offers a bike share system in the bay area called Bay Wheels. Bay Wheels has thousands of bikes available, its the most fun, convenient, and affordable way to explore the region. The goal of the investigation is to understand:

  • The different usage patterns of the bike service, and
  • To reveal how the different user groups, time periods and area affects these.

Dataset Overview¶

I have analysed Bay Wheels's publicly available trip data which was downloaded from the following url:

https://www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels/system-data

  • The data was combined from 12 separat monhtly data file from 2019.
  • The data required some slight wrangling before the analysis (handling missing values, standardizing station names and IDs and using the correct data types.
  • For 2019 there were 2,506,983 unique trips recorded in the dataset (although 3.9% of the data was removed during data cleaning)
  • Each trip is anonymized and includes columns of numeric, categorical and string data types.

Visualization 1: Proportion of Customer and Subscriber user groups¶

Bay Wheels currently distingishes between two customer types. Customer and Subsriber. In 2019, the proportion of the Customer user group was 19,6% while the proportion for the Subsribers are 80,4%.

The total number of rides recorded in the overall dataset is 2,506,983 of which 1,894,932 rides were taken by Subscriber and only 461,949 by the Customer group

Visualization 2: Hourly use-rate patterns over the week¶

The differences between the use-rates of the two useer groups reveal some very interesting patterns!

  • We can see that the Subscriber user group took much larger number of trips (we could also read this from the above pie chart) - please note the different ranges on the colorbars.
  • It is clearly visible that the peak periods during the day are the morning and evening rush hours for both usergroup, however, the Customers are proportionally more active during the weekend than the Subscribers.
  • We can also see that the Customers are somewhat less active durint the morning, but more active between the two peaks of the day (working hours).

What can be learn about the usergroups from this visualization?

  • Subscribers are typically using the service during the morning and evening rush hours, and they are less actie during the weekends. It soulds like the mambers of the Subsrciber usre group are typically using the service for commute to work.
  • While the Customer group is proportionally more active during the weekend and working hours than the subsriber group, and less active during the morning. It really sounds like the typical Customer is a tourist or a casual fun-rider, who is using the service to explore the area!

#Initialize the figure object
plt.figure(figsize=(15,7.5), dpi=600)

#Create the heatmap for the Customer user group
bikes_cust = bikes_clean.query('user_type == "Customer"')

#Create the matrix for the heatmap between 'hour_start' and 'weekday_start' columns 
#with the counts of the rides as the values
bikes_heat = pd.DataFrame(bikes_cust.groupby(['hour_start', 'weekday_start'])['duration_sec'].count()).reset_index()
bikes_heat = bikes_heat.pivot(index='hour_start', columns='weekday_start', values='duration_sec')

#map the matrix with seaborns heatmap function
ax1 = plt.subplot2grid((1,2),(0,0))
sb.heatmap(bikes_heat, cmap='PuRd');
plt.title('Customer', fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel('hour of days')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.yticks(rotation=0)


#Create the heatmap for the Subscriber user group
bikes_subs = bikes_clean.query('user_type != "Customer"')

#Creating the same matrix for the subsribers subgroup
bikes_subs = pd.DataFrame(bikes_subs.groupby(['hour_start', 'weekday_start'])['duration_sec'].count()).reset_index()
bikes_subs = bikes_subs.pivot(index='hour_start', columns='weekday_start', values='duration_sec')

#Plotting
ax2 = plt.subplot2grid((1,2),(0,1))
sb.heatmap(bikes_subs, cmap='PuRd')
plt.title('Subscriber', fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel('')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.yticks(rotation=0) 
plt.suptitle('Hourly Use-Rate Patterns Over the Week\nBetween Customer and Subscriber User Groups', fontsize=16);
ax2.yaxis.set_visible(False);

Visualization 3: Usage Patterns in Different Service Areas¶

There are three areas in where BayWeels provides service in the Bay Area:

  • San Francisco
  • East Bay
  • San Jose

Looking at the below plot, we can see that there are signifcant differences in the usage rates between the three are, both in case of the Subscriber and Customer user groups. With San Francisco having the highes and San Jose the lowet number of rides during 2019.
